Nihongo Place


1. Dictionary Form (辞書形 / じしょけい)
The dictionary form is the base form of a verb, as it appears in the dictionary. It is informal and used in casual speech or when conjugating into other forms.

Verb Groups:
Group 1 (う-verbs): Verbs that end with a consonant + う sound.
Example: 書く (to write), 飲む (to drink), 話す (to speak)
Group 2 (る-verbs): Verbs that end with a vowel + る sound.
Example: 食べる (to eat), 見る (to see)
Group 3 (Irregular verbs): Two irregular verbs: する (to do) and 来る (to come).

2. ます Form (Polite Form)
The ます form is the polite form of a verb, used in formal situations. It is derived from the dictionary form.

Conjugation Rules:
Group 1 (う-verbs): Change the final う sound to its corresponding い sound and add ます.
Example: 書く → 書きます (to write), 飲む → 飲みます (to drink)
Group 2 (る-verbs): Remove る and add ます.
Example: 食べる → 食べます (to eat), 見る → 見ます (to see)
Group 3 (Irregular verbs):
する → します (to do)
来る → 来ます (to come)


3. て Form (Connecting Form)
The て form is used to connect verbs, make requests, describe ongoing actions, or give permissions. It is one of the most versatile forms in Japanese.

Conjugation Rules:
Group 1 (う-verbs):
Verbs ending in う, つ, る → Change to って.
Example: 会う → 会って (to meet), 待つ → 待って (to wait), 取る → 取って (to take)
Verbs ending in む, ぶ, ぬ → Change to んで.
Example: 飲む → 飲んで (to drink), 遊ぶ → 遊んで (to play), 死ぬ → 死んで (to die)
Verbs ending in く → Change to いて.
Example: 書く → 書いて (to write)
Exception: 行く → 行って (to go)
Verbs ending in ぐ → Change to いで.
Example: 泳ぐ → 泳いで (to swim)
Verbs ending in す → Change to して.
Example: 話す → 話して (to speak)
Group 2 (る-verbs): Remove る and add て.
Example: 食べる → 食べて (to eat), 見る → 見て (to see)
Group 3 (Irregular verbs):
する → して (to do)
来る → 来て (to come)


he て form is one of the most versatile and important verb forms in Japanese. It is used in a variety of grammatical structures, such as making requests, connecting actions, describing ongoing actions, giving permissions, and more. Below are 10 examples of sentences using the て form, along with explanations of how it is used in each case.

10 Examples of て Form
1. Making a Request
ドアを開けてください。
(Please open the door.)

開ける (to open) → 開けて (て form)
～てください is used to politely ask someone to do something.
2. Connecting Actions
朝ごはんを食べて、学校に行きます。
(I eat breakfast and then go to school.)

食べる (to eat) → 食べて (て form)
The て form is used to connect two actions in sequence.
3. Describing an Ongoing Action
本を読んでいます。
(I am reading a book.)

読む (to read) → 読んで (て form)
～ている is used to describe an ongoing action or a current state.
4. Giving Permission
ここで写真を撮ってもいいです。
(You may take pictures here.)

撮る (to take a photo) → 撮って (て form)
～てもいいです is used to give permission to do something.
5. Prohibiting an Action
ここでタバコを吸ってはいけません。
(You must not smoke here.)

吸う (to smoke) → 吸って (て form)
～てはいけません is used to prohibit an action.
6. Asking for Help
ちょっと待ってください。
(Please wait a moment.)

待つ (to wait) → 待って (て form)
～てください is used to politely ask for help or action.
7. Expressing a Reason
電車が遅れて、会議に間に合いませんでした。
(The train was late, so I couldn’t make it to the meeting on time.)

遅れる (to be late) → 遅れて (て form)
The て form is used to connect two clauses, where the first clause explains the reason for the second.
8. Asking for Permission
トイレに行ってもいいですか？
(May I go to the bathroom?)

行く (to go) → 行って (て form)
～てもいいですか is used to ask for permission.
9. Listing Actions
家に帰って、宿題をして、寝ました。
(I went home, did my homework, and went to bed.)

帰る (to return home) → 帰って (て form)
する (to do) → して (て form)
The て form is used to list multiple actions in sequence.
10. Expressing a State
窓が開いています。
(The window is open.)

開く (to open) → 開いて (て form)
～ている is used to describe a state resulting from an action.
How to Form the て Form
Group 1 (う-Verbs)
Verbs ending in う, つ, る → Change to って
Example: 会う → 会って (to meet), 待つ → 待って (to wait), 取る → 取って (to take)
Verbs ending in む, ぶ, ぬ → Change to んで
Example: 飲む → 飲んで (to drink), 遊ぶ → 遊んで (to play), 死ぬ → 死んで (to die)
Verbs ending in く → Change to いて
Example: 書く → 書いて (to write)
Exception: 行く → 行って (to go)
Verbs ending in ぐ → Change to いで
Example: 泳ぐ → 泳いで (to swim)
Verbs ending in す → Change to して
Example: 話す → 話して (to speak)
Group 2 (る-Verbs)
Remove る and add て.
Example: 食べる → 食べて (to eat), 見る → 見て (to see)
Group 3 (Irregular Verbs)
する → して (to do)
来る → 来て (to come)
Summary of Uses for the て Form
Requests: ～てください (Please do...)
Example: ドアを閉めてください。 (Please close the door.)
Connecting Actions: ～て、～ (And then...)
Example: 朝ごはんを食べて、学校に行きます。 (I eat breakfast and go to school.)
Ongoing Actions: ～ている (I am doing...)
Example: 本を読んでいます。 (I am reading a book.)
Permission: ～てもいいです (You may do...)
Example: ここで写真を撮ってもいいです。 (You may take pictures here.)
Prohibition: ～てはいけません (You must not do...)
Example: ここでタバコを吸ってはいけません。 (You must not smoke here.)